TI  - Research on the spatial spillover effects and mechanisms of environmental regulation on the upgrading of WEEE industrial structure
AU  - Wang, Hongfei
AU  - Yan, Xiuxia
AU  - Zhang, Caiyun
AU  - Yang, Man
T2  - JOURNAL OF CLEANER PRODUCTION
AB  - Under the remanufacturing subsidy policy (RSP) and carbon tax policy (CTP), this paper explores the influence of environmental responsibility awareness on the operational decisions of enterprises within the dual-channel recycling closed-loop supply chain by constructing the Stackelberg model. Additionally, it examines the spatial spillover effects of both policies on the upgrading of the WEEE industrial structure. The research findings provide valuable insights for the government's selection of carbon emission reduction policies and for enterprises' engagement in environmental regulation. The study found that first, awareness of environmental responsibility positively contributes to the efficiency of WEEE recycling; however, it negatively impacts the improvement of corporate profits. Second, both carbon emission reduction policies can facilitate the development of remanufacturing. The recovery rate is higher under the recycling subsidy policy; however, the level of social welfare under both policies depends on specific product characteristics and varying boundary conditions. Third, enterprises can actively engage in environmental regulation by adjusting relevant production indicators to achieve high-quality development and foster organic integration with social green development.
