TY  - JOUR
TI  - Research on technology investment in the echelon utilization of retired power batteries for energy storage under the carbon trading mechanism
AU  - Liu, Juanjuan
AU  - Pan, Luyi
T2  - ENERGY
AB  - To promote international carbon emission reduction, the retired power batteries have been applied to energy storage for echelon utilization. This paper investigates the reverse closed-loop supply chain decisions, consisting of a echelon user, a third-party recycler, and an energy storage enterprise. The analysis encompasses models: whether echelon user investments blockchain technologies and carbon emission reduction technologies. The paper investigates optimal technology investment decisions under various models. The results indicate that: (1) Increasing government subsidy, the echelon utilization rate, and the carbon trading price can reduce carbon emissions during the processing and disposal of retired power batteries, and enable all parties in the supply chain to achieve higher profits; (2) Enhancing the testing/sorting level for retired power batteries enables recyclers to provide higher-quality power batteries suitable for echelon utilization to echelon users; (3) In the basic UB model, as well as the UBC and HB models with standalone investments in carbon emission reduction technology or blockchain technology respectively, none can achieve optimal performance. When echelon users simultaneously invest in blockchain technology and carbon emission reduction technology, both their profits and the total supply chain profits can reach the maximum among the four models.
